w current capacity.\n\n**Next-Generation V3 Broadband Satellites**\n*   **Timeline:** Deployment is expected to commence in the **second half of 2026**.\n*   **Capabilities:** Each V3 satellite is designed to offer **1 Tbps of downlink capacity**.\n*   **Starship Integration:** V3 satellites will be launched using Starship, which can deploy up to **60 V3 satellites per launch**. This represents a massive **twenty-fold increase** in downlink capacity deployed per launch compared to the Falcon 9.\n\n**Next-Generation Mobile Constellation (Gen2 / V2 Mobile)**\n*   **Timeline:** Deployment of next-generation **V2 Mobile satellites** is planned for **2027**.\n*   **Capabilities:** Gen2 services will offer comprehensive broadband data and IoT connectivity, eventually enabling 5G connectivity to unmodified cell phones and substantially eliminating global mobile "dead zones."\n*   **Starship Integration:** Starship is anticipated to deploy approximately **50 mobile satellites per launch**.\n*   **Spectrum Acquisition:** The Gen2 expansion is heavily tied to a **$19.6 billion acquisition of EchoStar** (equity and cash) for 65 MHz of U.S. spectrum and global Mobile Satellite Service (MSS) licenses. The acquisition is expected to close in **November 2027**.\n*   **Regulatory Status:** The FCC approved the EchoStar license transfer in May 2026, with remaining U.S. authorizations expected in Q2 or Q3 of 2026. Internationally, applications have been filed in nearly every target country, with limited approvals granted to date. Commercial Gen2 service in the U.S. cannot begin until the V2 Mobile satellites are in orbit and the spectrum acquisition is complete.',
