    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='## SpaceX Connectivity Capex vs. Amazon Project Kuiper: Comparative Deployment-Stage Assessment\n\n### 1. SpaceX Connectivity Segment Capex (from S-1)\n\nSpaceX\'s S-1 discloses the following Connectivity segment capital expenditures (which primarily reflect Starlink constellation build-out and ground infrastructure):\n\n| Period | Connectivity Capex |\n|---|---|\n| FY2023 | $2,455 million |\n| FY2024 | $3,498 million |\n| FY2025 | $4,178 million |\n| Q1 2026 | $1,332 million (annualized ~$5,328 million) |\n\nCumulative Connectivity capex over FY2023–Q1 2026 totals approximately **$11.5 billion** across roughly 2.25 years. SpaceX\'s Starlink constellation as of March 31, 2026 has approximately **9,600 satellites in orbit**, serves **10.3 million subscribers** across 164 markets, and generated **$11.4 billion in FY2025 Connectivity revenue**. The constellation is mature, revenue-generating, and now deploying next-generation V2 Mini satellites while planning V3 deployment via Starship in H2 2026.\n\n### 2. Amazon Project Kuiper Commitment\n\nAmazon has publicly committed **more than $10 billion** to Project Kuiper (announced alongside FCC authorization in July 2020). Industry analysts (e.g., Bank of America, Morgan Stanley) have estimated total program costs at **$16.5–$20 billion**. As of mid-2025, Amazon had launched only **~54 Kuiper satellites** (two batches of 27 via ULA Atlas V in April and June 2025) out of a planned **3,236-satellite constellation**. Amazon faces an FCC mandate to deploy at least **1,618 satellites (50%) by July 30, 2026**, a deadline it appears unlikely to meet at current launch cadence. The service has not yet achieved commercial viability—Amazon has rebranded it as "Amazon Leo" and guided for approximately **$1 billion of higher year-over-year Kuiper/Leo costs** in 2026 as it scales.\n\n### 3. What the Figures Suggest About Relative Deployment Stage\n\nThe comparison reveals a **massive asymmetry in constellation maturity**:\n\n- **SpaceX is in a mature, scaling phase.** Its $4.2 billion FY2025 Connectivity capex represents *sustaining and expanding* an already-operational constellation of ~9,600 satellites serving 10.3 million paying subscribers. SpaceX is spending to grow capacity (next-gen V3 satellites, mobile constellation, Starship-enabled mass launches), not to achieve initial deployment. The capex is being funded in part by $11.4 billion in segment revenue—the constellation is at least partially self-funding.\n\n- **Amazon is in a pre-commercial, early-deployment phase.** Its $10 billion+ commitment is a *forward-looking, multi-year program budget* for a constellation that has launched fewer than 60 satellites as of mid-2025. Amazon is currently **expensing** most Kuiper costs (production, launch, payroll) under "Technology and infrastructure" operating expenses rather than capitalizing them, because the service has not yet achieved commercial viability. The $10 billion floor represents total planned investment over the life of the program, not annual run-rate spending.\n\nIn short: SpaceX\'s annual Connectivity capex (~$4.2B in FY2025) is roughly **40% of Amazon\'s entire multi-year $10B+ commitment floor**, yet SpaceX is spending that amount *every year* to maintain and grow a constellation that is already 175× larger in orbit (~9,600 vs. ~54 satellites). This underscores that Amazon is years behind SpaceX in deployment and has not yet begun generating meaningful satellite broadband revenue.\n\n### 4. Analytical Limitation: Segment-Level Disclosure vs. Program-Level Commitment\n\nThe core analytical limitation is an **apples-to-oranges comparison** arising from three structural mismatches:\n\n1. **Temporal mismatch:** SpaceX\'s Connectivity capex is an *actual, incurred, annual figure* reported for specific fiscal periods. Amazon\'s $10 billion is a *cumulative, multi-year forward commitment* announced in 2020, with no disclosed annual breakdown or actual spend-to-date figure. Comparing a single year of SpaceX capex ($4.2B) against a multi-year Amazon commitment ($10B+) understates Amazon\'s annual run-rate and overstates the gap if Amazon is in a heavy-deployment year.\n\n2. **Scope mismatch:** SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment capex encompasses *all* connectivity-related capital spending—satellite manufacturing, launches, ground station infrastructure, user terminal production, and network operations for a mature, revenue-generating business. Amazon\'s $10 billion is a *program-specific* estimate for Kuiper constellation build-out only, and does not include broader AWS ground infrastructure or integration costs that may also support Kuiper.\n\n3. **Accounting treatment mismatch:** SpaceX capitalizes its Connectivity segment expenditures (reported as capex in segment disclosures). Amazon currently **expenses** most Kuiper costs as incurred under "Technology and infrastructure" operating expenses because the service has not achieved commercial viability. This means Amazon\'s Kuiper spending may not appear as capital expenditures at all in its 10-K, making direct capex-to-capex comparison impossible until Amazon begins capitalizing.\n\n### 5. Specific Amazon 10-K Line Items to Triangulate Kuiper Investment\n\nAn analyst seeking to triangulate Amazon\'s actual Kuiper spending should consult the following specific line items in Amazon\'s 10-K:\n\n**Primary line item: "Total net additions to property and equipment" by segment** (in the Segment Reporting footnote). This table breaks down capex by North America, International, AWS, and Corporate segments. However, Kuiper is **not separately disclosed** in any segment—its costs are likely embedded in the **"Corporate"** category ($2.3 billion in FY2025) or potentially within **AWS** ($96.5 billion in FY2025) given Kuiper\'s integration with AWS infrastructure. Amazon does not break out Kuiper as a sub-segment or separate reporting unit.\n\n**Secondary line items for triangulation:**\n\n- **"Other assets"** on the consolidated balance sheet ($82.1B in 2024; $122.6B in 2025): This line item explicitly includes **"satellite network launch services deposits"**—pre-launch deposits for Kuiper satellites. Changes in this balance year-over-year can signal the pace of Kuiper investment, though it is commingled with equity investments, content, intangibles, and deferred tax assets.\n\n- **"Prepaid expenses and other current assets"** ($6.3B in 2024; $6.9B in 2025): Also includes satellite launch services deposits that are expected to be utilized within 12 months.\n\n- **"Technology and infrastructure" operating expense** ($88.5B in 2024; $108.5B in 2025): This is where Amazon currently **expenses** Kuiper production, launch, and payroll costs. The $20 billion year-over-year increase is driven primarily by AWS/AI infrastructure, but Kuiper costs are embedded here and not separately broken out.\n\n- **"Construction in progress"** within Property and Equipment ($46.6B in 2024; $71.8B in 2025): Amazon has disclosed that it will **reclassify satellite launch deposits to CIP** once Kuiper achieves commercial viability. A future spike in CIP could signal the transition to commercial operations.\n\nThe fundamental challenge is that Amazon\'s 10-K provides **no standalone Kuiper line item** in either its income statement or segment reporting. An analyst must rely on management commentary (e.g., the Q1 2026 guidance citing ~$1 billion in incremental "Amazon Leo" costs), balance sheet changes in "Other assets," and the gap between total "Technology and infrastructure" expense growth and known AWS/AI drivers to estimate Kuiper\'s actual spend rate.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1018724/000101872426000004/amzn-20251231.htm",\n      "name": "Amazon.com, Inc. 10-K Annual Report (FY2025, filed February 6, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.advanced-television.com/2024/10/23/project-kuiper-a-16-billion-investment",\n      "name": "Advanced Television - Project Kuiper: A $16bn Investment (October 2024)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.morningstar.com/news/marketwatch/20241011279/amazon-faces-15-billion-project-kuiper-headwind-in-2025-after-satellite-launch-delay-morgan-stanley",\n      "name": "Morningstar / Morgan Stanley - Amazon Kuiper Headwind Analysis (October 2024)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
